			<ns0:name>pho...@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/117980525918552686609/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">When service runtime performs manifest lookup through Reverse Service, this uses OpenManifestEntry method on Reverse Interface. However, there is no mapping between the opened file and returned reference which means that later invocation to Unref cannot release the resource. Furthermore, since Chrome cannot delete the file until all references to the resource has been dropped, this could lead to potential DoS attack by depleting all disk space.

The Reverse Service should maintain mapping between the object reference returned to the service runtime and File object -- which should be an opaque void * returned from the OpenManifestEntry virtual function. This reference will be later used by Unref to release the resource.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-09-17T23:02:27.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2012-09-17T23:02:27.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>New</ns2:status><ns2:state>open</ns2:state><ns0:title>Reverse Service cannot release open manifest resources</ns0:title><ns2:label>Type-Defect</ns2:label><ns2:label>Pri-2</ns2:label><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/3035/comments/full" rel="replies" type="application/atom+xml" /><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=3035" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/full/3035" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /><ns2:stars>2</ns2:stars><ns2:id>3035</ns2:id></ns0:entry>